==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|absolucion|lang=enm}}, {{term|absolucioun|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|absolution|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|absolūtiōnem}}, accusative singular of {{m|la|absolūtiō||acquittal}}, from {{m|la|absolvō||absolve}}. See also ''[[absolve]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/æb.səˈljuː.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˌæb.səˈl(j)u.ʃn̩/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|uːʃən|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|ecclesiastical|lang=en}} An absolving of sins from ecclesiastical [[penalty|penalties]] by an authority. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=9}}</ref>
# Forgiveness of sins, in a general sense. {{defdate|First attested around 1150 to 1350.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# The form of words by which a penitent is [[absolved]]. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: {{rfquotek|Shipley}}
# An [[absolve|absolving]], or setting free from guilt, sin, or penalty; [[forgiven]]ess of an offense. {{defdate|First attested around 1350 to 1470.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''Government ... granting '''absolution''' to the nation.''
# {{context|civil|_|legal|obsolete|lang=en}} An [[acquittal]], or sentence of a judge [[declare|declaring]] an accused person [[innocent]]. {{defdate|First attested in the early 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} Delivery, in speech.
#: {{rfquotek|Ben Jonson}}

